//
// Exercise 16 — Closures: functions as values
//
//  So far every definition had a name. A CLOSURE, written \`fun(x) { body }\`, is
//  an anonymous function VALUE — you can pass it around, store it, and apply it.
//  It CAPTURES the variables in scope where it's written, so it can carry
//  configuration with it. And it's ordinary data: a closure unifies and reifies
//  like any term (it just can't be forged from untrusted JSON).
//
//  The prelude's \`map(f, list)\` and \`filter(pred, list)\` take a function — a
//  name OR a closure — and apply it across a cons list.
//
//  WORKED EXAMPLE — capture and apply:
//
//      exists k { k = 10; apply(fun(x) { [x, k] }, 5) }   → [5, 10]
//      map(fun(x) { [x] }, [1, [2, null]])                → [[1], [[2], null]]
//
//  YOUR TURN: double every number in the list — map a closure that turns \`x\`
//  into \`[x, x]\`. The closure body is wrong (it drops one copy).
